03838nam a22005055i 9780889208483DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20061987xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892084837 a10.51644/97808892084832doi  a(DE-B1597)667855  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aLIT0040802bisacsh04a813.52231 aCraig, Terrence, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRacial Attitudes in English-Canadian Fiction, 1905-1980 /cTerrence Craig. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©1987  a1 online resource (170 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tThe English-Canadian Attitude, 1905-1939 -- tThe Immigrant Reaction Before 1939 -- tThe Immigrant Reaction, 1939-1980 -- tThe Synthesis of Multiculturalism, 1939-1980 -- tKlein and Wiebe -- tConclusion -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRacial Attitudes in English-Canadian Fiction is a critical overview of the appearances and consequences of racism in English-Canadian fiction published between 1905 and 1980. Based on an analysis of traditional expressions in literature of group solidarity and resentment, the study screens English-Canadian novels for fictional representations of such feelings. Beginning with the English-Canadian reaction to the mass influx of immigrants into Western Canada after World War One, it examines the fiction of novelists such as Ralph Connor and Nellie McClung. The author then suggests that the cumulative effect of a number of individual voices, such as Grove and Salverson, constituted a counter-reaction which has been made more positive by Laurence, Lysenko, Richler and Clarke. The “debate” between these two sides, carried on in fictional and non-fictional writing, is seen to be in part resolved in synthesis after World War Two, as attitudes are forced by wartime alliances and intellectual pressures into a qualified liberalism. The author shows how single novels by Graham, Bodsworth, and Callaghan demonstrated a new concern for the exposure and eradication of racial discrimination, an attitude taken further by the works of Wiebe and Klein. The book concentrates on single texts that best portray deliberately or not, racist ideology or anti-racist arguments, and attempts to explain the arousal in Canada of such ideas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aLiterary Criticism. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920848340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889208483423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889208483/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles